      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks. Looking at `system_loop` again, the `sensor_interface.poll()` seems like a strong candidate. If `poll()` is allocating a new `SensorPacket` on the heap every time it finds data, then we're definitely losing that memory because nothing in the loop is actually calling `delete incoming;`.\n\nHowever, even if I fix that, I'm still worried about the \"creeping\" nature of it. It's so hard to spot because it's so gradual. Do you have any advice on how to catch these kinds of \"hidden\" leaks that only show up after hours of runtime, especially when I can't easily run a heavy tool like Valgrind on the actual ECU hardware?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To catch these gradual leaks, you might want to consider the following strategies:\n\n1. Implement a memory usage counter: Add a function that periodically checks the total heap usage and logs it. This won't fix the leak, but it'll give you a better idea of when the leak starts to become significant.\n\n2. Use a watchdog timer: If your ECU hardware supports it, configure a watchdog timer that triggers a system reset if memory usage exceeds a certain threshold. This will help you catch leaks that occur over longer periods.\n\n3. Simplify the code: Break down your code into smaller, more manageable functions. This can help you isolate and identify where leaks are happening.\n\n4. Use a memory leak detection tool: While Valgrind might not be an option, there are other tools available for embedded systems that can help you track down memory leaks. Look for a tool that is compatible with your development environment.\n\n5. Review your code: Take a close look at your code and look for any potential memory leaks. Pay attention to any functions that allocate memory and make sure that the memory is always freed.",
